It is well known that the painter of whom I now propose to speak has never suffered exclusion or acceptance at the hand of any academy. To such acceptance or such rejection all other men of any note have been and maybe liable. It is not “less well known that his work must always hold its place as second in significance and value to no work done by any painter of his time. Among the many great works of Mr. D. G. Rossetti, I know of none greater than his two latest These are 
 types of sensual beauty and spiritual, the siren and the sibyl. The one is a woman of the type of Adam's first wife ; she is a living Lilith, with ample splendour of redundant hair ; 




“ She excels

All women in the magic of her locks ; 

And when she winds them round a young man's neck

She will not ever set him free again.”
